SIMPLE: transmit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transmit
<hw>Trans*mit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Transmitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Transmitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>transmittere</ets>,
<ets>transmissum</ets>; <ets>trans</ets> across, over +
<ets>mittere</ets> to send: cf. F. <ets>transmettre</ets>. See
<er>Missile</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to pass over or
through; to communicate by sending; to send from one person or place to
another; to pass on or down as by inheritance; <as>as, to
<ex>transmit</ex> a memorial; to <ex>transmit</ex> dispatches; to
<ex>transmit</ex> money, or bills of exchange, from one country to
another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ancientest fathers must be next removed, as Clement of
Alexandria, and that Eusebian book of evangelic preparation,
<qex>transmitting</qex> our ears through a hoard of heathenish
obscenities to receive the gospel.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The scepter of that kingdom continued to be <qex>transmitted</qex>
in the dynasty of Castile.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To suffer to pass through; <as>as, glass
<ex>transmits</ex> light; metals <ex>transmit</ex>, or conduct,
electricity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transmittal</ent>⟦br⟧
